          "body": "Jeremiah 32 is organized around one of the strangest economic transactions in Scripture. A prophet under house arrest, in a city under active military assault, with the Babylonian siege ramps already at the walls (32:24), receives a divine command to purchase ancestral land in a village already in enemy-controlled territory (32:7). He does it: he weighs out seventeen shekels of silver (32:9), signs and seals the deed, calls witnesses, and hands the documents to his secretary Baruch before an audience of fellow prisoners (32:10-12). Then he stores the deed in a clay jar for long-term preservation (32:14). The irrationality of the act by every economic calculus is the point. The prophet's obedience is the sermon. Walter Brueggemann rightly notes that Jeremiah's act embodies hope as a political and economic posture — not as feeling, but as investment. The sign-act says what no oracle alone could: the God who is ending this city is the same God who has already written the deed for its recovery."
