          "body": "The chapter's theological spine is a single Hebrew word — pala (too difficult, too extraordinary, beyond capacity) — appearing in verse 17 in Jeremiah's prayer and in verse 27 in God's reply. Jeremiah opens his prayer with the confession: 'Nothing is too difficult for You' (32:17). He then proceeds to lay out the evidence of God's past power (creation, Exodus, gift of the land), acknowledges the justice of the exile, and finally admits his bewilderment: God has commanded him to buy a field while the city falls (32:25). God's response does not begin with an explanation. It begins with a question: 'Is anything too difficult for Me?' (32:27). The theological move is decisive. Jeremiah's confession was formally correct but functionally insufficient — he believed in omnipotence as a doctrine while struggling to act on it in the immediate crisis. God's question is not a rebuke; it is a pastoral extension of the same confession. Jeremiah said 'nothing'; God says 'then — is this thing I am about to do beyond Me?' The question reopens every foreclosed possibility."
